The technique to obtain the coronal temperature (T) and speed (V) involves quantifying the shape change and red shift of the K-corona spectrum (see, e.g., Ichimoto et al., 1996). Since we have four data points on the spectrum, we can compare the observed spectrum against the theoretical spectrum to see what T and V values give the best match between the two spectra. The computation of the theoretical K-corona spectrum requires T, V, and density (n) of electrons along the line-of-sight. Assuming T and V to be constant along the line of sight, we model the density distribution of the streamer using a density multiplier A given by 2A=P0exp[−12(φ−P1P2)2]\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
