				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\approx 6$\end{document} days. The same streamer structure was studied by Morgan and Cook (2020) two rotations after the BITSE observations. Their compilation of streamer densities at 5 Rs is in the range (5 – 11) × 104 cm−3. We have not yet determined the electron density from the BITSE data yet, but we inverted the calibrated LASCO/C2 pB image (see Figure 19) to get a density of ≈7.6×104\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\approx 7.6\times 10^{4}$\end{document} cm−3, which is within the above density range. After complete calibration, we plan to obtain the density from BITSE images. Assuming a constant mass flux and using the constraints on proton flux measured by Parker Solar Probe, these authors estimated an outflow in the streamers of 50 – 120 km s−1 at 4 Rs, and 90 – 250 km s−1 at 8 Rs. Our speeds are slightly larger, but consistent with these estimates, given the large uncertainty in our speed measurements.

BITSE was launched on 18 September 2019, which corresponds to the minimum of Solar Cycle 24. The prominent features in the solar minimum corona are the equatorial streamers. The narrow streamer observed by BITSE is in good agreement with the geometric properties obtained by SOHO/LASCO in the overlapping physical domain. For the equatorial streamer on the west limb, we obtained a temperature of ≈1.0±0.3\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\approx 1.0 \pm 0.3$\end{document} MK and a flow speed of ≈260\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
				\usepackage{amsmath}
				\usepackage{wasysym}
				\usepackage{amsfonts}
				\usepackage{amssymb}
				\usepackage{amsbsy}
				\usepackage{mathrsfs}
				\usepackage{upgreek}
				\setlength{\oddsidemargin}{-69pt}
				\begin{document}$\approx 260$\end{document} km s−1. These parameters are in the general range of other estimates in the literature obtained indirectly. These results are preliminary, and we expect to refine them by (i) adding more images that need to be processed taking account of the slightly different BITSE altitudes, and (ii) completing post-launch calibrations.

BITSE is the first joint solar mission between NASA and KASI, a step to increase technology readiness level toward a next-generation coronagraph (Cho et al., 2017). Through BITSE, the NASA and KASI coronagraph teams demonstrated the technology successfully and are developing a coronagraph for the Experiment COronal Diagnostic Experiment (CODEX) that will be deployed on the International Space Station 2023. CODEX will overcome the sky brightness and the short observing duration that resulted in insufficient signal-to-noise ratio beyond ≈7\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
